Note that the peak of the current graph (Figure~\ref{22012.eps}) has not changed from the earlier series LC circuit (the one with the 1 $\Omega$ token resistance in it), even though the resistance is now 100 times greater.  The only thing that has changed is the ``sharpness'' of the curve.  Obviously, this circuit does not resonate as strongly as one with less series resistance (it is said to be ``less selective''), but at least it has the same natural frequency!
 

 

It is noteworthy that antiresonance has the effect of dampening the oscillations of free-running LC circuits such as tank circuits.  In the beginning of this chapter we saw how a capacitor and inductor connected directly together would act something like a pendulum, exchanging voltage and current peaks just like a pendulum exchanges kinetic and potential energy.  In a perfect tank circuit (no resistance), this oscillation would continue forever, just as a frictionless pendulum would continue to swing at its resonant frequency forever.  But frictionless machines are difficult to find in the real world, and so are lossless tank circuits.  Energy lost through resistance (or inductor core losses or radiated electromagnetic waves or . . .) in a tank circuit will cause the oscillations to decay in amplitude until they are no more.  If enough energy losses are present in a tank circuit, it will fail to resonate at all.
 

 

Antiresonance's dampening effect is more than just a curiosity: it can be used quite effectively to eliminate \textit{unwanted} oscillations in circuits containing stray inductances and/or capacitances, as almost all circuits do.  Take note of the following L/R time delay circuit: (Figure~\ref{02107.eps})
 

 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{02107.eps} 
\caption{\sl L/R time delay circuit } 
\label{02107.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

The idea of this circuit is simple: to ``charge'' the inductor when the switch is closed.  The rate of inductor charging will be set by the ratio L/R, which is the time constant of the circuit in seconds.  However, if you were to build such a circuit, you might find unexpected oscillations (AC) of voltage across the inductor when the switch is closed. (Figure~\ref{02108.eps})  Why is this?  There's no capacitor in the circuit, so how can we have resonant oscillation with just an inductor, resistor, and battery?
 

 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{02108.eps} 
\caption{\sl Inductor ringing due to resonance with stray capacitance. } 
\label{02108.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

All inductors contain a certain amount of stray capacitance due to turn-to-turn and turn-to-core insulation gaps.  Also, the placement of circuit conductors may create stray capacitance.  While clean circuit layout is important in eliminating much of this stray capacitance, there will always be some that you cannot eliminate.  If this causes resonant problems (unwanted AC oscillations), added resistance may be a way to combat it.  If resistor R is large enough, it will cause a condition of antiresonance, dissipating enough energy to prohibit the inductance and stray capacitance from sustaining oscillations for very long. 
 

\index{Resonance, mechanical}
\index{Antiresonance, mechanical}
 

Interestingly enough, the principle of employing resistance to eliminate unwanted resonance is one frequently used in the design of mechanical systems, where any moving object with mass is a potential resonator.  A very common application of this is the use of shock absorbers in automobiles.  Without shock absorbers, cars would bounce wildly at their resonant frequency after hitting any bump in the road.  The shock absorber's job is to introduce a strong antiresonant effect by dissipating energy hydraulically (in the same way that a resistor dissipates energy electrically).
 

\bigskip 
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{REVIEW:}
\item Added resistance to an LC circuit can cause a condition known as \textit{antiresonance}, where the peak impedance effects happen at frequencies other than that which gives equal capacitive and inductive reactances.
\item 
Resistance inherent in real-world inductors can contribute greatly to conditions of antiresonance. One source of such resistance is the \textit{skin effect}, caused by the exclusion of AC current from the center of conductors.  Another source is that of \textit{core losses} in iron-core inductors.

\item In a simple series LC circuit containing resistance (an ``RLC'' circuit), resistance does \textit{not} produce antiresonance.  Resonance still occurs when capacitive and inductive reactances are equal.
\end{itemize}


\section{ Q and bandwidth of a resonant circuit }
\index{Q, resonant circuit}
\index{Bandwidth, resonant circuit}
 

The \textit{Q, quality factor,}  of a resonant circuit is a measure of the ``goodness'' or quality of a resonant circuit. A higher value for this figure of merit corresponds to a more narrow bandwith, which is desirable in many applications. More formally, Q is the ratio of power  stored to power dissipated in the circuit reactance and resistance, respectively: 
 

\begin{table} [hbtp!]
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
~      Q = P$_{stored}$/P$_{dissipated}$ = I$^{2}$X/I$^{2}$R
~      Q = X/R
~      where:      X = Capacitive or Inductive reactance at resonance
~                  R = Series resistance.
\endgroup 
\end{table}
 

This formula is applicable to series resonant circuits, and also parallel resonant circuits if the resistance is in series with the inductor. This is the case in practical applications, as we are mostly concerned with the resistance of the inductor limiting the Q. Note: Some text may show  X and R interchanged in the ``Q'' formula for a parallel resonant circuit. This is correct for a large value of R in parallel with C and L. Our formula is correct for a small R in series with L.
 

 

A practical application of ``Q'' is that voltage across L or C in a series resonant circuit is Q times total applied voltage. In a parallel resonant circuit, current through L or C is Q times the total applied current.
 


\subsection{ Series resonant circuits}
 

A series resonant circuit looks like a resistance at the resonant frequency. (Figure~\ref{22048.eps}) Since the definition of resonance is X$_{L}$=X$_{C}$, the reactive components cancel, leaving only the resistance to contribute to the impedance. 
% Split for multiple ref's per paragraph
The impedance is also at a minimum at resonance.  (Figure~\ref{22049.eps}) Below the resonant frequency, the series resonant circuit looks capacitive since the impedance of the capacitor increases to a value greater than the decreasing inducitve reactance, leaving a net capacitive value. Above resonance, the inductive reactance increases, capacitive reactance decreases, leaving a net inductive component.
 

 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{22048.eps} 
\caption{\sl At resonance the series resonant circuit appears purely resistive. Below resonance it looks capacitive. Above resonance it appears inductive.  } 
\label{22048.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

Current is maximum at resonance, impedance at a minumum. Current is set by the value of the resistance.  Above or below resonance, impedance increases.
 

 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{22049.eps} 
\caption{\sl Impedance is at a minumum at resonance in a series resonant circuit. } 
\label{22049.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

The resonant current peak may be changed by varying the series resistor, which changes the Q.  (Figure~\ref{22050.eps}) This also affects the broadness of the curve. A low resistance, high Q circuit has a narrow bandwidth, as compared to a high resistance, low Q circuit.  Bandwidth in terms of Q and resonant frequency:
 

\begin{table} [hbtp!]
\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
~         BW = f$_{c}$/Q
~         Where  f$_{c}$ = resonant frquency
~                Q = quality factor
\endgroup 
\end{table}
 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{22050.eps} 
\caption{\sl A high Q resonant circuit has a narrow bandwidth as compared to a low Q } 
\label{22050.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

Bandwidth is measured between the 0.707  current amplitude points.  The 0.707 current points correspond to the half power points since P = I$^{2}$R, (0.707)$^{2}$ = (0.5).  (Figure~\ref{22051.eps})
 

 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{22051.eps} 
\caption{\sl Bandwidth, $\Delta$f is measured between the 70.7\% amplitude points of series resonant circuit. } 
\label{22051.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

 

\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
~          BW = $\Delta$f = f$_{h}$-f$_{l}$ = f$_{c}$/Q 
~          Where f$_{h}$ = high band edge,  f$_{l}$ = low band edge 
~
~          f$_{l}$ = f$_{c}$ - $\Delta$f/2 
~          f$_{h}$ = f$_{c}$ + $\Delta$f/2
~          Where  f$_{c}$ = center frequency (resonant frequency)
\endgroup 
\bigskip 
 

In Figure~\ref{22051.eps}, the 100\% current point is 50 mA. The 70.7\% level is 0.707(50 mA)=35.4 mA. The upper and lower band edges read from the curve are 291 Hz for f$_{l}$  and 355 Hz for f$_{h}$. The bandwidth is 64 Hz, and the half power points are $\pm$ 32 Hz of the center resonant frequency:
 

\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
~
~          BW = $\Delta$f = f$_{h}$-f$_{l}$  = 355-291 = 64 
~          f$_{l}$ = f$_{c}$ - $\Delta$f/2 = 323-32 = 291 
~          f$_{h}$ = f$_{c}$ + $\Delta$f/2 = 323+32 = 355 
\endgroup 
\begin{table} [hbtp!]
 

Since BW = f$_{c}$/Q:
 

\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
~          Q = f$_{c}$/BW = (323 Hz)/(64 Hz) = 5
\endgroup 
\end{table}


\subsection{ Parallel resonant circuits}
 

A parallel resonant circuit is resistive at the resonant frequency. (Figure~\ref{22052.eps}) At resonance  X$_{L}$=X$_{C}$, the reactive components cancel. 
% Split for multiple ref's per paragraph
The impedance is maximum at resonance.  (Figure~\ref{22053.eps}) Below the resonant frequency, the parallel resonant circuit looks inductive since the impedance of the inductor is lower, drawing the larger proportion of current. Above resonance, the capacitive reactance decreases, drawing the larger current,  thus, taking on a capacitive characteristic.
 

 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{22052.eps} 
\caption{\sl A parallel resonant circuit is resistive at resonance, inductive below resonance, capacitive above resonance. } 
\label{22052.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

Impedance is maximum at resonance in a parallel resonant circuit, but decreases above or below resonance. Voltage is at a peak at resonance since voltage is proportional to impedance (E=IZ). (Figure~\ref{22053.eps})
 

 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{22053.eps} 
\caption{\sl Parallel resonant circuit: Impedance peaks at resonance. } 
\label{22053.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

A low Q due to a high resistance in series with the inductor produces a low peak on a broad response curve for a parallel resonant circuit. (Figure~\ref{22054.eps}) conversely, a high Q is due to a low resistance in series with the inductor. This produces a higher peak in the narrower response curve. The high Q is achieved by winding the inductor with larger diameter (smaller gague), lower resistance wire.
 

 
\begin{figure}[hbtp!] 
\centering 
\includegraphics{22054.eps} 
\caption{\sl Parallel resonant response varies with Q. } 
\label{22054.eps} 
\end{figure}

 

The bandwidth of the parallel resonant response curve is measured between the half power points. This corresponds to the 70.7\% voltage points since power is proportional to E$^{2}$. ((0.707)$^{2}$=0.50) Since voltage is proportional to impedance, we may use the impedance curve. (Figure~\ref{22055.eps})
 

 
